HmF (i.e., a BmF-monoid where all\nthe minimal factorizations of a given element have the same length), or\nminimally factorial (i.e., a BmF-monoid where each element has an essentially\nunique minimal factorization). Finally, we prove how to realize certain\nintervals as sets of minimal lengths in $\\mathcal P_{\\text{fin},1}(H)$.\n  Many proofs come down to considering sumset decompositions in cyclic groups,\nso giving rise to an intriguing interplay with Arithmetic Combinatorics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 29 Apr 2018 12:14:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 9 Aug 2019 10:31:19 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 1 Dec 2020 10:33:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-09-08"}
